<% content_for :title, "Basecamp Home screen rework" %>
<h2><strong>Design Exercise:</strong><br>Making Basecamp&rsquo;s Home screen feel like home.</h2>
<p>
  Hi again, 37signals! I'm excited to share my redesign of Basecamp's home screen.
</p>
<p>
  I decided to dive into one overall concept, showing various states of that concept over time. In the link below, you'll
  see the prototype along with a list of links on the bottom to those states. I also link to those states in this write-up
  as I discuss my thought process.
</p>
<%= render "shared/external_link_button", path: basecamp_first_time_path, text: "My rework of Basecamp's home screen", target: "_blank" %>
<p class="note">
  <strong>Note:</strong> I tried to make the feel match Basecamp as closely as possible, but took some liberties to not get bogged down on minutiae. 
  For example, for some iconography, I went with <%= link_to "Font Awesome", "https://fontawesome.com/", target: "_blank" %> just to get the idea across.
  I wanted to demonstrate I can stylize things in a Basecamp way but still put some of my own personality into the design. 
</p>
<hr>

<h3>The North Star: A focus on <strong>feeling good</strong></h3>
<p>
  Unlike Basecamp's Home screen, most home screens typically bludgeon you with data&mdash;charts, graphs, percentages of something. 
  The stuff that makes for a good marketing site screenshot. The stuff that makes you feel like the app is working.
</p>
<p>
  In real life, it all just makes you feel bad. Have you ever looked at a productivity chart and thought, "Wow, we're doing great"? Neither have I.
</p>
<p>
  So, that's not where I went with this.
</p>
<p>
  Basecamp's Home screen is also the very first screen a new customer sees after Jason's welcome message. 
  It's an opportunity to introduce not just Basecamp the product, but Basecamp the philosophy. 
  What is this software about? What is it <strong>not</strong> about?
</p>
<p>
  <strong>Basecamp is not about hard metrics</strong>. 
  It's not about &ldquo;why are so many things red&rdquo; or &ldquo;why is that number so high&rdquo; 
  or &ldquo;why is that line going down&rdquo;. Those things might tell you some contrived bad news.
  Let's trust that our customers are trying to do good work.
</p>
<p>
  <strong>Basecamp is about momentum</strong>. Taking a meaningful step down a path today. Celebrating the progress you just made.
  Re-evaluating work from the vantage point right now. Communication over calculation.
</p>
<p>
  The home screen should exude making you <em>feel</em> this. It should make you feel...good.
</p>
<p>
  In control.<br>
  In meaningful thought.<br>
  Calm.<br>
  Focused.<br>
  Productive.<br>
  Satisfied.<br>
</p>
<p>
  Nothing that the internet, social media, or AI seems to be about today.
</p>
<p>
  This was my North Star for the week. Making the Home screen not just a launching pad for everything else, 
  but feel like a home. A place that's inviting for the latest customer. A place a 15-year Basecamper 
  might not have known they missed.
</p>
<hr>
<h3>The Briefcase</h3>
<p>
  The old Home screen was about your projects, with some stuff about you at the bottom.
  This Home screen is about <strong>you</strong> first. The main area (which I'm calling "the briefcase" internally
  but doesn't have to be called anything on the app) shows you two sections.
</p>
<div class="figure-container smaller">
  <figure>
    <%= link_to image_tag("dd-og-site.webp", alt: "A screenshot of the original DoneDone marketing site"), "https://web.archive.org/web/20100927203150/http://www.getdonedone.com/index.aspx", target: "_blank", class: "link-thumbnail" %>
  </figure>
</div>
<h4>What's on tap</h4>
<p>
  This section consolidates your assigned to-dos, cards, events, and automatic check-ins across all your projects in one place,
  in the following order:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>If you've marked any assignments <em>Up Next</em>, they go at the top.</li>
  <li>Items due today (or have an end date of today) go next.</li>
  <li>After that, it shows the next two days where you have something due.</li>
</ul>
<p class="note">
  <strong>Logic thoughts:</strong> I would show 6-8 items at most. These would naturally go away as you check off to-dos or
  mark a card as "Done" or "Not Now", bringing the next items up. 
</p>
<p>
  Underneath, a button to "more items on tap" would expand the list. A link to 
  your overdue assignments would jump you to the "My assignments with dates" section of "My assignments" since
  overdue assignments show at the top of that page.
</p>
<p>
  Right underneath the "What's on tap" header is a short sentence: "Your upcoming assignments, events, and check-ins."
  The first two would link to "My assignments" and "My schedule". I don't believe there is a "My check-ins" page at the global level yet,
  so that may not link at all. If this person isn't tied to any project with check-ins, we could omit that last part to prevent confusion.
</p>
<p>
  For first time customers, we could stub the default "My Project" project with a sample to-do and event, and also turn on the 
  Card Table by default with a card. <%= link_to "Here's what the intro page would look like to a first time customer.", "/", target: "_blank" %>
</p>
<h4>Don&rsquo;t forget</h4>
<p>
  I love the "Don't forget" concept. It's a great way to curate all the other forms of communication in Basecamp regardless of where they come from. 
  I think that list should show up on the Briefcase, not just in the Hey! navigation. This way, the briefcase shows you:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>
    The items you're responsible for that are due at a certain time.
  </li>
  <li>
    The items that don't necessarily have a due date but are important to you.
  </li>
</ul>
<p>
  The Home screen now gives you a greater sense of control and calm. Assurance that an important thing hasn't slipped through the cracks. 
  You'd want to come here to make sure you didn't forget anything, and <%= link_to "an empty briefcase", "/", target: "_blank" %> should make you feel good too!
</p>
<hr>
<h3>A calm thought to start your morning</h3>
<p>
  We all know the benefits of reading a few pages of a book before you go to bed instead of doom-scrolling through your phone. 
  But what about the reverse? What about reading a short, thought-provoking piece of non-fiction
  to rev up your brain in the morning before you hit that first task rather than...doom-scrolling through your phone?
</p>
<p>
  So, I thought it would be fun to surface one <em>philosophical-thought-by-Basecamp</em> each day. No algorithm. No random rotations.
  One thought a day that lives as a little sticky note at the bottom of the briefcase. (I originally had this at 
  the top but thought that might be too invasive.)
</p>
<p>
  For example, Jason's (probably) written hundreds of posts that could fit this daily dopamine hit.
  <%= link_to "Here", "https://world.hey.com/jason/doing-what-you-think-not-what-you-thought-60bb5bef", target: "_blank" %>
  <%= link_to "are", "https://world.hey.com/jason/go-do-business-00af347c", target: "_blank" %>
  <%= link_to "five", "https://world.hey.com/jason/subjectivity-in-productivity-e0b4e2ee", target: "_blank" %>
  <%= link_to "recent", "https://world.hey.com/jason/making-it-happen-vs-letting-it-happen-28d4b4c0", target: "_blank" %>
  <%= link_to "ones", "https://world.hey.com/jason/the-work-of-art-and-the-work-of-the-art-28d4b4c0", target: "_blank" %>.
  There are hundreds of chapters to pull from <em>Rework</em> or <em>It Doesn't Have to Be Crazy At Work</em> as well.
</p>
<p>
  We'd have to curate carefully. They can't feel like we're trying to sell someone. They should be appropriate for the times. 
  But they ought to enhance the things that Basecamp stands for. 
</p>
<p>
  Maybe we start with a month's worth&ndash;they just go away after that. 
  Maybe some people love it and we keep adding onto the stack over time. 
  If it doesn't work (or is too much work), we just ditch it.
</p>
<p class="note">
  <strong>If there was a week two:</strong> I would implement a toggle that could just store a <span class="code">localStorage</span>
  property to turn this off or back on again.
</p>
<hr>
<h3>Feeling the momentum of your day</h3>
<p>
  I started by saying that Basecamp is not about metrics. But, that doesn't mean we should shy away from 
  numbers altogether. We can use them to celebrate, not reprimand.
</p>
<p>
  The usual experience of completing tasks in software isn't very motivating.
  You complete a to-do? It simply grays out.
  Drag a card to &ldquo;Done&rdquo;? It just goes away.
  Sign off your Zoom meeting? A dark screen with your face on it.
</p>
<p>
  As you accomplish things during the day, the Home screen <em>celebrates</em> this. 
  Not with a small increment in a pie chart. Not over-the-top, cringy confetti raining down from the top of the screen. 
  Just a nudge.
</p>
<p>
  Notice how empty the top area of the Home screen feels at the beginning of the day? As things get done, "stickers"
  will start appearing there. Maybe it'll remind folks of that feeling when you got one of those
  "Great job!" scratch-n'-sniff stickers for completing your worksheet in grade school.
</p>
<ul>
  <li>
    <strong>To-Dos</strong>: When you complete a to-do, it shows up as the light blue sticker. Complete one and there's
    a checkmark on the lower-right. Complete more, and the checkmark turns into a number. This would link to your "Completed assignments" page.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Cards</strong>: Same idea for cards marked "Done".
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Events</strong>: If an event has a time, once that time has passed, we can assume it's done and show it as the yellow sticker.
    (A little more backend work here I know). This would link to your "My schedule" page.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Automatic check-in</strong>: Finish your write-up? It shows as the purple sticker. 
    This could link to the first check-in you've done that day if there are multiple.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Time-tracked</strong>: If you've tracked time, it shows as the green sticker with your total cumulative hours on the lower-right.
    This would link to your "Timesheets" page.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Boosts</strong>: If you've boosted, it shows as the red sticker with your total cumulative boosts on the lower-right.
    This would link to your "My Boosts" page.
  </li>
</ul>
<p class="note">
  <strong>Design nuance:</strong> I like the idea of a number that sits on the lower-right within the sticker rather than a 
  floating red circle on the upper-right. The latter is synonymous with "I'm behind" on your inbox or your text messages. 
  Not particularly calming.
</p>
<p>
  At the end of a productive day's work, <%= link_to "your Home screen should fill with colors", "/", target: "_blank" %>.
  And if you didn't get things done that way because maybe that wasn't how your day lined up? 
  Fine too! It's still calm. No slap on the wrist.
</p>
<p>
  This area would reset at the end of each day, hinting at the idea that Basecamp is about looking forward, not back.
</p>
<p>
  The other benefit of Stickers? They might lead you to places in Basecamp you might not know about. 
  For example, it took me awhile to even know there was a page that tracked all my boosts or a central timesheet.
</p>

<p class="note">
  <strong>If there was a week two:</strong> I would implement the stickers so they would auto-update. For example, on checking 
  off a to-do, I'd animate the to-do sticker with a little pop effect. In a real project scenario, I would also work with a back-end developer
   to update the numbers in real-time.
  (I haven't used Turbo streams yet, so this would be a great learning experience.)
  Also I had some other design ideas like more of a mosaic of boosts...
</p>
<hr>
<h3>What about all those projects?</h3>
<p>
  In the very center of the Home screen is the project navigator that reads "Dive into a project". Click, find, and go. 
  There's an activeness and direction to the verb "dive" I like here rather than just saying "go" or "jump".
</p>
<ul>
  <li>
    <strong>Pinned projects and stacks</strong> show up at the top.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Recent projects</strong> not in those lists show up after.
  </li>
  <li>
    Older projects show up last.
  </li>
</ul>
<p>
  After debating this for awhile, I decided I didn't want to lose any of the features of the existing project card design. 
  For folks that may do more <em>managing of everything</em> rather than specific task work, the old design works very well.
  They might find the new design doesn't fit them at all. So one of two approaches might work:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>
    The "Manage projects & templates" link at the top would surface the existing page (minus the "Your Schedule" and "Your Assignments" sections at the bottom).
  </li>
  <li>
    Or, ditch that link altogether, and put the entire project cards section below the briefcase inside the same kind of white container. 
  </li>
</ul>
<p>
  Lastly, I did remove the company name and logo on the Home screen. We don't show either on any other page, so my hunch is that the benefit
  of cleaning that area up for these other design goals was worth it. But, I could be totally wrong about this and we could certainly fit it back 
  in to the top of the page
</p>
